"1381–12 november 1448","1383–1450":"1383–1450","1410–1485":"1410–1485","1381–1448":"1381–1448","1448":"1448","12 November 1448":"12 november 1448","1410":"1410","1485":"1485","1450":"1450","1383":"1383","1381":"1381","07 Feb 1415":"7 februari 1415","Blackrod, Lancashire, England":"Blackrod, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ruthin, Denbighshire, Wales":"Ruthin, Denbighshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Earls Barton, Northamptonshire, England":"Earls Barton, Northamptonshire, England"},"en":{"1381–12 November 1448":"1381–12 November 1448","1383–1450":"1383–1450","1410–1485":"1410–1485","1381–1448":"1381–1448","1448":"1448","12 November 1448":"12 November 1448","1410":"1410","1485":"1485","1450":"1450","1383":"1383","1381":"1381","07 Feb 1415":"7 February 1415","Blackrod, Lancashire, England":"Blackrod, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Ruthin, Denbighshire, Wales":"Ruthin, Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Earls Barton, Northamptonshire, England":"Earls Barton, Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Astley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places in England called Astley (in Lancashire, Shropshire, Warwickshire, Worcestershire, and Yorkshire), from Old English <i>ēast</i> ‘east’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. The modern surname seems to be particularly associated with the one in Warwickshire. See also   Astle  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Astle","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in Cheshire called Astle, from Old English <i>ēast</i> ‘east’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’. There may also have been some confusion with <i>Asthall</i> and   Astley  . Or occasionally this may be a topographic name denoting residence on an ‘east hill’ (from Middle English <i>ast</i> + <i>hill</i> or <i>hull</i>), i.e. a hill to the east of a settlement.","English: perhaps also a habitational name from Astwell, Northamptonshire, from Old English <i>ēast</i> ‘east’ + <i>wielle</i> ‘spring’.","English: habitational name from Asthall, Oxfordshire, from Old English <i>ēast</i> ‘east’ + <i>halh</i> ‘nook’."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Astley was born in 1381, in Blackrod, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. She married Sir Richard Whetehill, Knight on 7 February 1415, in Ruthin, Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 12 November 1448, in Ruthin, Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 67."},"et":{"1381–12 November 1448":"1381–12. november 1448","1383–1450":"1383–1450","1410–1485":"1410–1485","1381–1448":"1381–1448","1448":"1448","12 November 1448":"12. november 1448","1410":"1410","1485":"1485","1450":"1450","1383":"1383","1381":"1381","07 Feb 1415":"7. veebruar 1415","Blackrod, Lancashire, England":"Blackrod, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ruthin, Denbighshire, Wales":"Ruthin, Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Earls Barton, Northamptonshire, England":"Earls Barton, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1381–12 November 1448":"1381–12. marraskuuta 1448","1383–1450":"1383–1450","1410–1485":"1410–1485","1381–1448":"1381–1448","1448":"1448","12 November 1448":"12. marraskuuta 1448","1410":"1410","1485":"1485","1450":"1450","1383":"1383","1381":"1381","07 Feb 1415":"7. helmikuuta 1415","Blackrod, Lancashire, England":"Blackrod, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Ruthin, Denbighshire, Wales":"Ruthin, Denbighshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Earls Barton, Northamptonshire, England":"Earls Barton, Northamptonshire, England"},"fr":{"1381–12 November 1448":"1381–12 novembre 1448","1383–1450":"1383–1450","1410–1485":"1410–1485","1381–1448":"1381–1448","1448":"1448","12 November 1448":"12 novembre 1448","1410":"1410","1485":"1485","1450":"1450","1383":"1383","1381":"1381","07 Feb 1415":"7 février 1415","Blackrod, Lancashire, England":"Blackrod, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Ruthin, Denbighshire, Wales":"Ruthin, Denbighshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","Earls Barton, Northamptonshire, England":"Earls Barton, Northamptonshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Joan Astley est née en 1381, à Blackrod, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a épousé Sir Richard Whetehill, Knight le 7 février 1415, à Ruthin, D